version: 1
display_name: VCFA-9X-000017 - The VMware Cloud Foundation vCenter Server must enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15 minute time period.
global_description: |-
  By limiting the number of failed login attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFA-9X-000017
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000065
  cci:
    - CCI-000044
  nist:
    - AC-7 a
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_vcenter:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation vCenter Server must enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15 minute time period.
    control_id: VCFA-9X-000017
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Administration >> Single Sign On >> Configuration >> Local Accounts >> Lockout Policy.

      Review the following lockout policies.

      Maximum number of failed login attempts
      Time interval between failures

      If "Maximum number of failed login attempts" is not set to 3, this is a finding.

      If "Time interval between failures" is not set to 900 seconds or more, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      By limiting the number of failed login attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.
    remediation: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Administration >> Single Sign On >> Configuration >> Local Accounts >> Lockout Policy.

      Click "Edit".

      Set the "Maximum number of failed login attempts" to 3 and the "Time interval between failures" to 900 seconds then click "Save".
